05995nam a22008415i 9783110365832DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2018941005  a97831103658327 a10.1515/97831103658322doi  a(DE-B1597)428238  a(OCoLC)1041994386  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aQA433b.K49 2018 4aQA433b.K467 2018 7aMAT0030002bisacsh04a515.632231 aKhoromskaia, Venera, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTensor Numerical Methods in Quantum Chemistry /cVenera Khoromskaia, Boris N. Khoromskij. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 289 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Rank-structured formats for multidimensional tensors -- t3. Rank-structured grid-based representations of functions in ℝd -- t4. Multiplicative tensor formats in ℝd -- t5. Multidimensional tensor-product convolution -- t6. Tensor decomposition for analytic potentials -- t7. The Hartree–Fock equation -- t8. Multilevel grid-based tensor-structured HF solver -- t9. Grid-based core Hamiltonian -- t10. Tensor factorization of grid-based two-electron integrals -- t11. Fast grid-based Hartree–Fock solver by factorized TEI -- t12. Calculation of excitation energies of molecules -- t13. Density of states for a class of rank-structured matrices -- t14. Tensor-based summation of long-range potentials on finite 3D lattices -- t15. Range-separated tensor format for many-particle systems -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe conventional numerical methods when applied to multidimensional problems suffer from the so-called "curse of dimensionality", that cannot be eliminated by using parallel architectures and high performance computing. The novel tensor numerical methods are based on a "smart" rank-structured tensor representation of the multivariate functions and operators discretized on Cartesian grids thus reducing solution of the multidimensional integral-differential equations to 1D calculations. We explain basic tensor formats and algorithms and show how the orthogonal Tucker tensor decomposition originating from chemometrics made a revolution in numerical analysis, relying on rigorous results from approximation theory. Benefits of tensor approach are demonstrated in ab-initio electronic structure calculations. Computation of the 3D convolution integrals for functions with multiple singularities is replaced by a sequence of 1D operations, thus enabling accurate MATLAB calculations on a laptop using 3D uniform tensor grids of the size up to 1015. Fast tensor-based Hartree-Fock solver, incorporating the grid-based low-rank factorization of the two-electron integrals, serves as a prerequisite for economical calculation of the excitation energies of molecules. Tensor approach suggests efficient grid-based numerical treatment of the long-range electrostatic potentials on large 3D finite lattices with defects.The novel range-separated tensor format applies to interaction potentials of multi-particle systems of general type opening the new prospects for tensor methods in scientific computing. This research monograph presenting the modern tensor techniques applied to problems in quantum chemistry may be interesting for a wide audience of students and scientists working in computational chemistry, material science and scientific computing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCalculus of tensors. 0aQuantum chemistry. 0aTensor algebra. 4aTensornumerische Methoden. 7aMATHEMATICS / Applied.2bisacsh1 aKhoromskij, Boris N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut